  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(5) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Certain of the sect of the Pharisees which believed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—This is the first distinct mention of the conversion of any of the Pharisaic party, but there had been a drift in that direction going on for some time, beginning during our Lord’s ministry (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 12:42",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and showing itself in the moderate counsels of Gamaliel (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 5:38-39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The position which they occupied was that of accepting Jesus as a teacher sent from God, proved by the Resurrection to be the Christ, and as such the Head of a kingdom which was to present to mankind a restored and glorified Judaism, the Law kept in its completeness, the Temple ritual still maintained, Gentiles admitted only on their confessing their inferiority and accepting the sign of incorporation with the superior race. It appears, from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 2:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", that here, as in so many later controversies, the general issue was debated on an individual case. Was Titus—a Greek, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "i.e., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "a Gentile, whom St. Paul had brought up with him—to be circumcised, or not? Was he to be admitted to communion with the Church, or treated as a heathen? Here, probably, there was no official rank as in the case of Cornelius, no previous transition stage in passing through the synagogue as a proselyte of the gate. He was a Gentile pure and simple, and as such his case was a crucial one. Circumcision, however, did not stand alone. It carried with it every jot and tittle of the Law, the Sabbaths and the feasts, the distinction between clean and unclean meats. It may be noted that the position which Titus occupied in this controversy gave him a special fitness for the work afterwards assigned to him, of contending against the party of the circumcision, with their “Jewish fables” and false standards of purity (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 1:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 1:14-15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "15:1-6 Some from Judea taught the Gentile converts at Antioch, that they could not be saved, unless they observed the whole ceremonial law as given by Moses; and thus they sought to destroy Christian liberty. There is a strange proneness in us to think that all do wrong who do not just as we do. Their doctrine was very discouraging. Wise and good men desire to avoid contests and disputes as far as they can; yet when false teachers oppose the main truths of the gospel, or bring in hurtful doctrines, we must not decline to oppose them.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "But there rose up ... - It has been doubted whether these are the words of Paul and Barnabas, relating what occurred at Antioch, or whether they are the words of Luke recording what took place at Jerusalem. The correct exposition is probably what refers it to the latter. For:",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(1) This seems to be the most obvious interpretation.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(2) the use of the words \"rose up\" implies that. Those who disturbed the church at Antioch are said to have come down from Judea Acts 15:1, and if this place referred to that occurrence, the same words would have been retained.",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "(2) the use of the words \"rose up\" implies that. Those who disturbed the church at Antioch are said to have come down from Judea ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 15:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ", and if this place referred to that occurrence, the same words would have been retained.",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(3) the particular specification here of \"the sect of the Pharisees\" looks as if this was an occurrence taking place at Jerusalem. No such specification exists respecting those who came down to Antioch; but it would seem here as if this party in Jerusalem resolved still to abide by the Law, and to impose those rites on the Christian converts. However, this interpretation is by no means certain.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Which believed - Who maintained or taught.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "That it was needful ... - See the notes on Acts 15:1. ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": "That it was needful ... - See the notes on ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 15:1",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "",
            "text": ". ",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "4. And when they were come to Jerusalem—This was Paul's Third Visit to Jerusalem after his conversion, and on this occasion took place what is related in Ga 2:1-10. (See there).",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "were received of the church, and the apostles and elders—evidently at a meeting formally convened for this purpose: the deputation being one so influential, and from a church of such note.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "they declared all things that God had done with them—(See on [2018]Ac 14:14-27).",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Poole's Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " If these words be taken for St. Luke’s, the penman of this book, then they declare, that in the church of Jerusalem there were some that did abet the opinion of the necessity of circumcision; but if, (as most probably we may), we take them for the words of St. Paul, they then are part of his narrative to the church there, of what had happened at Antioch. ",
        "children": []
      },
